# .cursorrules  — drop this file in the ROOT of your host repository.
#
# Cursor IDE loads it automatically and injects the contents as persistent
# system context for every AI chat in this workspace.  The result: you never
# need to re-explain the project when you start a new conversation.
#
# ─── HOW TO USE ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# 1. Copy this file to your host repo root and rename it:
#
#      cp CodeVisualizer/Readme/.cursorrules.example .cursorrules
#
# 2. Fill in the sections below that are marked  ← EDIT THIS
#    (project name, stack, current focus, etc.).
#
# 3. Keep it short — a few hundred words max.  Cursor prepends the full file to
#    every prompt, so verbose rules hurt more than they help.
#
# 4. Re-run CodeVisualizer any time the codebase changes significantly:
#
#      ./CodeVisualizer/scripts/regenerate_mermaid_output.sh
#
#    This refreshes:
#      • mermaid_output/<target>/ai_context_primer.md   ← paste into new chats
#      • mermaid_output/<target>/codebase_index.json    ← machine-readable index
#      • mermaid_output/<target>/*.mmd                  ← diagrams
#
# 5. After any meaningful code change, record it:
#
#      # Log it in the AI memory (free-form note):
#      ./CodeVisualizer/scripts/ai_note.sh "Fixed X; why; where to look."
#
#      # Log it in the structured changelog (machine+human readable):
#      ./CodeVisualizer/scripts/changelog.sh \
#          --type fix \
#          --what "Fixed price rounding in invoice" \
#          --why  "Float precision caused cent errors in PDF exports" \
#          --files "src/invoice.py src/utils/currency.py"
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## Project identity

**Project name:** <!-- ← EDIT THIS: e.g. "Acme Invoice Service" -->
**Purpose:** <!-- ← EDIT THIS: one sentence, e.g. "Generates and emails PDF invoices for Shopify orders." -->
**Language / stack:** <!-- ← EDIT THIS: e.g. "Python 3.11 · FastAPI · PostgreSQL · Celery · Redis" -->
**Repo layout:** <!-- ← EDIT THIS: e.g. "src/api/ (FastAPI routes), src/models/ (SQLAlchemy), src/tasks/ (Celery), tests/" -->

## Current focus / active work

<!-- ← EDIT THIS: what is being worked on right now, so the AI starts in the right context.
     Example:
     Working on the `InvoiceGenerator` class in `src/invoice.py`.
     The goal is to fix float precision in `calculate_total()` and add PDF attachment support.
-->

## Architecture decisions and constraints

<!-- ← EDIT THIS: non-obvious rules the AI must respect.
     Examples:
     - No ORM lazy loading — always use explicit `.options(joinedload(...))`.
     - All monetary values are stored as integers (cents), never floats.
     - Do not touch `legacy/` — it is vendor code and must not be modified.
     - Background jobs go through Celery; never call them synchronously.
-->

## Where the AI should look first

When asked about the project structure or a bug, prefer reading these files in order:

1. `mermaid_output/<target>/ai_context_primer.md` — compact project brief
2. `CodeVisualizer/Readme/AI_PROJECT_MEMORY.md` — recent change history and reasons
3. `CHANGELOG.md` — structured log of every modification (what, why, which files)
4. `mermaid_output/<target>/codebase_index.json` — full class/function index
5. `mermaid_output/<target>/callgraph.mmd` — who calls what
6. `mermaid_output/<target>/erd.mmd` — entity relationships

## Coding style

<!-- ← EDIT THIS: house rules the AI should follow.
     Examples:
     - PEP 8, max line length 100.
     - Use type hints on all public functions.
     - No bare `except`; always catch specific exceptions.
     - Tests live under `tests/` and use pytest.
     - Docstrings use Google style.
-->

## Things the AI must NOT do

<!-- ← EDIT THIS.
     Examples:
     - Do not install new dependencies without asking.
     - Do not reformat files that are not part of the current task.
     - Do not modify database migration files — always create new ones.
-->

## Quick reference commands

```bash
# Re-generate all diagrams and ai_context_primer.md
./CodeVisualizer/scripts/regenerate_mermaid_output.sh

# Append a free-form note to the AI memory log
./CodeVisualizer/scripts/ai_note.sh "Note about what changed and why."

# Append a structured entry to CHANGELOG.md
./CodeVisualizer/scripts/changelog.sh \
    --type feat \
    --what "Added PDF attachment to invoice emails" \
    --why  "Customers requested downloadable invoices" \
    --files "src/invoice.py src/email_sender.py"
```
